SUMMARY:The Junction! Keele Street and Dundas Street West!
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or fo
 r signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticke
 t amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the 
 following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nThe West Toron
 to Junction is back! It has been reworked and a new route explores more of
  this historic area. Prior to this\, the walk crossed Dundas to the north\
 , this tour remains on the southern side and extends to Keele Street and t
 he real industrial heart of the area.\n\nOne of Toronto's most walkable an
 d fascinating neighbourhoods\, and is steeped in history.\n\nLocated in To
 ronto's west end\, west of Lansdowne Avenue\, the area is surrounded on th
 ree sides by railway lines: the CNR mainline to the west\, Metrolinx to th
 e east\, and the CPR east-west line to the north. Dundas Street is the hea
 rt and main street of the Junction\, but also provides the area with a sou
 thern boundary\, creating a compact well defined neighbourhood.\n\nThe vil
 lage was a centre for industry\, and was lined with railway tracks hence t
 he name the Junction. Paint\, ceramics\, chemicals\, and the Ontario Stock
  Yards were also nearby. Industry gave way to the worker's residences\, an
 d by the 1950s the neighbourhood was multicultural consisting of Maltese\,
  Italian\, Polish\, and Macedonian immigrants. Later\, the area became pre
 dominantly Portuguese.\n\nThis area was also an area of churches set in a 
 garden like setting. Now most of the churches have been converted to resid
 ences\, but we still have them as historic markers of a lost era.\n\nThis 
 walk is for all fitness levels.\n\nThe meeting place for our walking adven
 ture is outside the Annette Street Branch of the Toronto Public Library at
  145 Annette Street in West Toronto\, just a block south of Dundas Street 
 West.\n\nThis tour has a ticket price of $15.00 per person!\n\n\\*\\* **Pl
 ease note: Please e-transfer the ticket amount when booking your space for
  this tour! You can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n**torontohist
 orywalks@gmail.com**
